er an intermittent lodger in London. His impressive home gave Shakespeare significant social status and was crucial to his relationship with Stratford-upon-Avon.Archaeology helps to inform biography in this innovative and refreshing study which presents an overview of the site from prehistoric times through to a richly nuanced reconstruction of New Place when Shakespeare and his family lived there, and beyond. This attractively illustrated book is for anyone with a passion for archaeology or Shakespeare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aElizabeth.  aHugh Clopton.  aJames Halliwell.  aLady Bernard.  aShakespeare.  aStratford-upon-Avon.  abrick-and-timber house.  aearly investments.  aeducation.  amarriage.  awork.1 aColls, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aColls, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdmondson, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMitchell, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610650640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526106506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526106506/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles